Japanese Government Bonds May Decline on Machine Orders, Advancing Stocks

-- B y   Y o s h i a k i   N o h a r a
-- 
2011-03-08T22:59:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/japanese-government-bonds-may-decline-on-machine-orders-advancing-stocks.html
Japan’s bonds may fall as a report
today is forecast to show machine orders increased in January,
damping demand for the relative safety of government debt.  Benchmark 10-year yields may climb to a two-week high on
speculation local stocks will rise after crude-oil prices
retreated from a 29-month high. Bonds may also drop on
expectations investors will reduce their debt holdings to
prepare for tomorrow’s auction of five-year notes.  “Should machine orders come out stronger than expected,
that will add to recent improvements in the economic outlook and
may increase downward pressure on bonds in the morning,”  Kazuhiko Sano , chief strategist at Tokai Tokyo Securities Co.,
wrote in a research note today.  Ten-year bond futures for March delivery last traded at
139.56 in  London  from 139.59 at the 3 p.m. close at the Tokyo
Stock Exchange yesterday. The contract will open for trading at
9 a.m. Tokyo time.  The benchmark 10-year bond hasn’t traded yet today at Japan
Bond Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.
The yield on the 1.3 percent bond due March 2021 rose 2.5 basis
points to 1.295 percent yesterday.  Ten-year yields reached 1.315 percent on March 4, the
highest since Feb. 18. A basis point is 0.01 percentage point.  Machine Orders  Machine orders gained 3 percent in January from the
previous month when they rose 1.7 percent, according to a
Bloomberg News survey of economists before the Cabinet Office
reports the data at 8:50 a.m. today in Tokyo.  Nikkei 225 Stock Average futures rose, trading at 10,570 in  Chicago  from 10,520 in  Osaka  yesterday. Crude oil for April
delivery dropped 42 cents to settle at $105.02 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange  yesterday.  The Ministry of Finance will sell 2.4 trillion yen ($29
billion) of five-year notes tomorrow. The prior five-year sale
on Feb. 16 drew bids worth 3.56 times the amount on offer,
compared with a bid-to-cover ratio of 3.97 at the January sale.  Primary dealers, which are required to bid at government
debt sales, often reduce holdings of bonds before an auction in
case prices decline before they can pass on the new securities
to investors.  The 1.2 percent bond due in December 2020 closed at 99.43
to yield 1.265 percent yesterday, according to the Bloomberg Yen
Bond Fixing Price. The level is an average rate set at 6:30 p.m.
in Tokyo by Daiwa Securities Capital Markets Co., Citigroup
Global Markets Japan Inc., Mizuho Securities Co. and Mitsubishi
UFJ Morgan Stanley Securities Co.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Yoshiaki Nohara in Tokyo at 
 ynohara1@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Rocky Swift at   rswift5@bloomberg.net . 